    "Terence E. Fretheim, Thomas B. Slater": "This passage places a premium on unity, oneness. Christ has\nmade the two into one, thereby creating concord where enmity\n[v_Eph_2_1] [v_Eph_2_2] [v_Eph_2_3] [v_Eph_2_4] [v_Eph_2_5] [v_Eph_2_6] [v_Eph_2_7] [v_Eph_2_8] [v_Eph_2_9] [v_Eph_2_10] [v_Eph_2_11] [v_Eph_2_12] [v_Eph_2_13] [v_Eph_2_14] [v_Eph_2_15] [v_Eph_2_16] [v_Eph_2_17] [v_Eph_2_18] [v_Eph_2_19] [v_Eph_2_20] [v_Eph_2_21] [v_Eph_2_22] Ephesians 2:1-22\nresided previously (2:14-16). The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` peace that Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` has wrought has\ngiven Christians access to God the Father \u201cin one Spirit\u201d (2:18).\nFinally, \u201cthe family of God\u201d (\n22. E.g., V. P. Furnish, 2 Corinthians (AB; New York: Doubleday, 1984) 371\u201383;\nR. P. Martin, 2 Corinthians (Waco TX: Word, 1986) 190\u201395.\n22. Best provides six reasons for his position. First,\n\u201cbeing subject\u201d (hypotassomenoi) continues the participles in vv. 19\nand 20 that are \u201cdependent on the imperative be filled of\nv. 18b\n[boldface in the text].\u201d Second, \u201c5:21 deals with the relationship of\nall believers to one another,\u201d while 5:22\u20136:9 deals only with relation-\nships within Christian households. Third,\n22. Second, 5:22\u20136:9 deals with a fresh subject, the household codes.\nThird, the theme of 5:22\u20136:9 is subordination. Fourth, the participle\nin\nv. 22,"
