  "15": {
    "Terence E. Fretheim, Thomas B. Slater": "Fifth, the absence of a verb at the start of a\nnew unit has parallels in other Pauline writings. Finally, while\nphobos/phobeomai (\u201cfear; reverence\u201d) in vv. 21 and 33 \u201cmay form an\ninclusion . . . , it does not necessarily follow that\n4:15-16), but it also conveys considera-\ntion of the humanity of the other person\nin the relationship.\n[Golden Wedding\nAnniversary]\nMacDonald argues that the Christ-\nChurch analogy becomes important in\nsubsequent verses, seeing its origin in the\nHebrew Bible where the relationship between Yahweh and Israel is\noften compared to a marriage.19 The book of Hosea is the best\nexample of this in the HB. I am persuaded by MacDonald\u2019s argu-\nment. Moreover, as Israel had corporate meaning in the HB, so too\nthe Church has corporate meaning in the book of Ephesians (cf.\n[v_Rev_19_1] [v_Rev_19_2] [v_Rev_19_3] [v_Rev_19_4] [v_Rev_19_5] [v_Rev_19_6] [v_Rev_19_7] [v_Rev_19_8] [v_Rev_19_9] [v_Rev_19_10] Rev 19:1-10).\nThe `[group_Word_Luk_1]` phrase \u201cHe Himself (being) savior of the body\u201d anticipates\nthe exhortation to husbands in 5:25-\nappeared in Greco-Roman religious writings. For example,\nSibylline Oracles 1, 73 and 3, 35 use it to refer to God as do LXX\n[v_Psa_24_5]\n15. Jay, E. G. New Testament Greek: An Introductory Grammar. London: SPCK,"
  },
